(1, 1, '2012-09-20 02:32:07', '2012-09-20 02:32:07', '<p>The Canarian Deputy Ministry for Tourism thru the Tourist Board (Turismo) have always required apartments used by tourists to be registered with them to ensure taxes are paid, standards are maintained, and those letting commercially are accountable for their actions.</p>\r\n<p>Originally under (law 3/1986) any owner could rent his or her apartment to tourists so long as it was registered with the Turismo. The property could be registered under the individual owner''s name, or thru any management agent with a tourist license.</p>\r\n<p>In 1995 a new tourist law (law 7/1995) was introduced.  This law introduced unity of exploitation, which meant that each complex had to have a single management company responsible for all of the apartments rented out within the complex.  The thinking behind the change in the law was that previously there were so many entities letting on each complex that it was impossible for the tourist board to hold anyone accountable for services provided.</p>\r\n<p>This law has not been rigorously enforced but as a result of political and economic pressure, the Canarian Government has committed itself to identify the 400,000 or so "illegal beds" and around 650,000 "clandestine beds” thought to be available in the Canaries. Quite how this figure has been established is uncertain but it considerably exceeds the 430,00 official tourist beds in the Canaries registered with Turismo.</p>\r\n<p>Seventeen inspectors have been recruited and charged with finding and fining owners of residential apartments who let commercially outside the law.  The definition of commercial letting has never been tested in court, though it is generally taken to mean the letting to holidaymakers for commercial gain.  As a result, "friends and family" is the one exception granted by the law to residential apartment owners.   It should also be pointed out that long-term residential lets or temporary lets of 3 months duration or more are considered to fall outside the tourist laws and as a result are not affected.</p>\r\n<p>If in fact this Canarian Government initiative is successful, any owner who secures a let through a holiday website or advert and is apprehended by the Inspectorate will be hard pressed to claim the holidaymaker is a friend.  Until such time as the situation eases, serious consideration should be given to employing a method of advertising that ensures any such commercial transactions are kept as much “below the radar” as is reasonably possible.</p>\r\n<p>This document does not constitute legal advice and the accuracy of the information herein is not guaranteed.</p>', 'Letting in Tenerife and Canarian Law', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'letting-in-tenerife-and-canarian-law', '', '', '2012-09-23 18:18:16', '2012-09-23 18:18:16', '', 0, 'http://web-dropbox.com/clients/tenerife/?p=1', 0, 'post', '', 0),
